{"title_page": "Himalaya Airlines", "text_new": "{{Infobox airline\n| airline = Himalaya Airlines\n| image = Himalaya_Airlines.png\n| image_size = 100\n| alt = Logo of Himalaya Airlines\n| IATA = H9<ref name=\"chavprofile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/HYL | title=Himalaya Airlines | work=[[ch-aviation]] | accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n| ICAO = HIM<ref name=\"chavprofile\" />\n| callsign = HIMALAYA<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Order/7340_2F_Bsc_w_Chgs_1-3_Contractions.pdf#page=181 | title=7340.2F with Change 1 and Change 2 and Change 3 | work=[[Federal Aviation Administration]] | date=15 September 2016 | accessdate=24 January 2017 | page=3\u20131\u201351}}</ref>\n| founded = 19 August 2014\n| commenced = 31 May 2016\n| aoc = 084/2015<ref>{{cite web |title=Civil aviation Report 2017 |url=http://www.caanepal.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Final-Report-2017.pdf |publisher=Civil Aviation Authority of Nepal |accessdate=14 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907044552/http://www.caanepal.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Final-Report-2017.pdf |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| ceased = \n| bases = \n| hubs = [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] {{small|(Kathmandu)}}\n| secondary_hubs = \n| focus_cities = \n| frequent_flyer = \n| lounge = \n| alliance = \n| fleet_size = 4\n| destinations = 10\n| company_slogan = \n| parent = \n| num_employees = \n| headquarters = [[Gairidhara|Gairidhara, Kathmandu]], Nepal<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us|publisher=Himalaya Airlines|accessdate=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118094416/http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| key_people = {{bulleted list\n|Zhou Enyong<br>{{small|President}}\n|Vijay Shrestha<br>{{small|Vice President}}\n}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Himalaya Airlines''' ({{lang-ne|\u0939\u093f\u092e\u093e\u0932\u092f \u090f\u0905\u0930\u0932\u093e\u0907\u0928\u094d\u0938\u094d}}, ''{{transl|ne|BGN/PCGN|Him\u0101laya earal\u0101ins}}'') is a [[Nepal|Nepalese]] [[airline]] operating from [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] in Kathmandu, Nepal. Himalaya Airlines was founded in 2014 as a [[joint venture]] between Yeti World Investment Group and [[Tibet Airlines]]. It launched operations in May 2016 with a single [[Airbus A320]]. The airline flies to ten destinations as of 24 January 2020.\n\n[[File:D-AVVU -- Himalaya Airlines -- A320-214SL -- MSN 7503 -- 9N-ALV (32049204731).jpg|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 taxiing at [[Hamburg Finkenwerder Airport|Finkenwerder Airport]] in Germany]]\n[[File:9N-ALW@PKX (20191027170009).jpg|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 wearing the new livery on a final approach to Beijing-Daxing.]]\n\n==History==\nHimalaya Airlines is the second attempt of [[Yeti Airlines|Yeti Airlines Group]] to launch an international airline based in Nepal, following the collapse of [[Fly Yeti]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Arabia begins Nepal hub operations and launches flyyeti.com |url=http://www.flyyeti.com:80/Air%20Arabia%20begins%20Nepal%20hub%20operations%20and%20launches%20FlyYeti.html |publisher=Fly Yeti |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206232908/http://www.flyyeti.com/Air%20Arabia%20begins%20Nepal%20hub%20operations%20and%20launches%20FlyYeti.html |archivedate=6 February 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInitially,{{When|date=July 2018}} [[Tibet Airlines]] and the Himalaya Infrastructure Fund had stakes in the airline alongside Yeti World Investment, an affiliate of Yeti Airlines Group.<ref name=\"firstprovingflight\">{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2015-02-27/himalaya-conducts-proving-flight.html | title=Himalaya conducts 'proving' flight | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=27 February 2015 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn order to obtain its [[air operator's certificate]], Himalaya Airlines leased aircraft from Yeti Airlines and conducted its first proving flights in February 2015.<ref name=\"firstprovingflight\" /> Launch plans were delayed by the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-01-27/himalaya-airlines-plans-to-start-ops-by-march-end.html | title=Himalaya Airlines plans to start ops by March-end | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=27 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> The airline inducted its first aircraft, an [[Airbus A320]], on March 9 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-03-10/himalaya-airlines-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft.html | title=Himalaya Airlines takes delivery of first aircraft | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=10 March 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Himalaya Airlines launched operations on May 31 2016 with flights between [[Kathmandu]] and [[Doha]].<ref name=\"launch31may\">{{cite news | url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-07/07/c_135496535.htm | title=China-Nepal JV airline to start daily Kathmandu-Doha flight | work=[[Xinhua News Agency]] | date=7 July 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Flights from Kathmandu to [[Colombo]] started in October, marking the resumption of scheduled flights between Nepal and Sri Lanka after 28 years but the flights were soon suspended.<ref name=\"launchcmb\">{{cite news | url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-begins-kathmandu-colombo-flight/ | title=Himalaya Airlines begins Kathmandu-Colombo flight | work=[[The Himalayan Times]] | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Himalaya Airlines served as the [[Air transports of heads of state and government#Nepal|governmental aircraft of Nepal]], when Prime Minister [[Khadga Prasad Oli]] used Himalaya's services on his inaugural visit to [[China]]. This was the first time that the head of the Nepalese Government did not use state owned airline; resulting public outcry.<ref>{{cite web|title=PM to fly to China with Himalaya|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-03-18/pm-to-fly-to-china-with-himalaya.html|publisher=The Kathmandu Post|accessdate=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airline initially focused on unconventional routes; such as [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]] and [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]] as opposed to highly demanded middle-eastern destinations but they were quickly terminated. After all, Himalaya ended up operating to [[Dammam]], [[Saudi Arabia]] as well as [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]]. In the months leading to '''Visit Nepal 2020''', Himalaya focused on the market in China, as Chinese are ranked second among the most number of travellers that visit to Nepal. In October 2019, Himalaya Airlines launched direct service to Beijing's newly constructed [[Beijing Daxing International Airport | Daxing International Airport]] making it the only airline in Nepal to connect the capitals of [[Nepal]] and [[China]].{{cn}}\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal]], Himalaya Airlines carried out rescue and evacuation charter flights<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines Chartered flight returns back from Guangzhou; Mission Accomplished |url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/himalaya-airlines-chartered-flight-returns-back-from-guangzhou-mission-accomplished/ |publisher=Aviation Nepal |accessdate=29 April 2020}}</ref> while all of its scheduled flights were grounded from March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131329/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n==Corporate affairs==\nAt the time of its establishment, Tibet Airlines held a 49% stake in Himalaya Airlines, while Yeti World Investment (an affiliate of Yeti Airlines Group) owned the remaining 51%.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nepalitimes.com/article/nation/Nepal-is-still-on-european-safety-blacklist,3442 | title=A Himalayan mess | work=[[Nepali Times]] | date=2016 | accessdate=17 February 2017 | author=Rai, Om}}</ref> Zhao Guo Qiang was the airline's first president while [[Ang Tshering Sherpa (entrepreneur)|Ang Tshering Sherpa]] served as [[chairman of the board]] until his death in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=About us |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118094416/https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us |archivedate=18 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, Himalaya Airlines underwent [[restructuring|ownership restructuring]], for which the shares of Tibet Airlines were transferred to [[Tibet Civil Aviation Development and Investment]]. Subsequently, the logo and livery were changed. The blue, dark blue as well as white blend of livery and logo was changed with orange and blue combination. Though, the fuselage retained its white color.<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines announces new partnership with Tibet Civil Aviation |url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2019/09/30/himalaya-airlines-announces-new-partnership-with-tibet-civil-aviation |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> Currently, [[Zhou Enyong]] serves as the president of Himalaya Airlines.<ref>{{cite web |title=Management Team |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/about/corporate/management-team |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe airline is headquartered in [[Gairidhara]], Kathmandu.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/address.php | title=Corporate office address | work=Himalaya Airlines | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\nAs a result of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], [[ Nepal Government]] has suspended all domestic and international flights until 15 May 2020.{{cn|date=April 2020}}.\n\nPrior to this, Himalaya Airlines served the following destinations:<ref>{{cite web |title=Flight Schedule|url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/travel/flights-schedule |publisher=Himalayan Airlines |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Country\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|City\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|IATA\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|ICAO\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Airport\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Notes\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Refs\n|-\n|[[Bangladesh]]||[[Dhaka]]||DAC||VGHS||[[Shahjalal International Airport]]||||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-direct-flight-to-dhaka/|title=Himalaya Airlines direct flight to dhaka|publisher=The Himalayan Times|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[China]]||[[Beijing]]||PKX||ZBAD||[[Beijing Daxing International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines plans Beijing Daxing launch in late October 2019|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286470/himalaya-airlines-plans-beijing-daxing-launch-in-late-oct-2019/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Changsha]]||CHX||ZGHA||[[Changsha Huanghua International Airport]]||  ||<ref name=\"H9W19\">{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines Winter 2019 network adjustment|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287507/himalaya-airlines-w19-network-adjustment-as-of-08nov19/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Chongqing]]||CKG||ZUCK||[[Chongqing Jiangbei International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya begins direct flights to Chongqing |url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-10-23/himalaya-begins-direct-flights-to-chongqing.html |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=23 October 2018 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines resumes Chongqing service in late-jan 2020|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288631/himalaya-airlines-resumes-chongqing-service-in-late-jan-2020/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Guiyang]]||KWE||ZUGY||[[Guiyang Longdongbao International Airport]]||  ||<ref name=\"H9W19\"/>\n|- \n|[[Shenzhen]]||SZX||ZGSZ||[[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prasain |first1=Sangam |title=As other airports institute stringent screening, TIA installs thermal scanners and a health desk |url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/28/as-other-airports-institute-stringent-screening-tia-installs-thermal-scanners-and-a-health-desk |website=The Kathmandu Post |publisher=Kantipur Media Group |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Malaysia]]||[[Kuala Lumpur]]||KUL||WMKK||[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]]|| ||\n|-\n|[[Myanmar]]||[[Yangon]]||RGN||VYYY||[[Yangon International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref>{{cite web |title=Airline stops Yangon to Kathmandu flights |url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/airline-stops-yangon-kathmandu-flights.html |publisher=Myanmar Times |accessdate=1 October 2018 |date=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nepal]]||[[Kathmandu]]||KTM||VNKT||[[Tribhuvan International Airport]]||{{Airline hub}}||\n|-\n|[[Qatar]]||[[Doha]]||DOH||OTHH||[[Hamad International Airport]]|| ||\n|-\n|[[Saudi Arabia]]||[[Dammam]]||DMM||OEDF||[[King Fahd International Airport]]|| ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines' Festival Bonanza: Daily direct flight from Kathmandu to Dammam|url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/press/detail/himalaya-airlines-festival-bonanza-daily-direct-flight-from-kathmandu-to-dammam|publisher=Himalaya Airlines|accessdate=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903074206/http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/press/detail/himalaya-airlines-festival-bonanza-daily-direct-flight-from-kathmandu-to-dammam|archive-date=3 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sri Lanka]]||[[Colombo]]||CMB||VCBI||[[Bandaranaike International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines launches inaugural flight to Colombo |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-launches-inaugural-flight-colombo/ |publisher=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=1 October 2018 |date=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[United Arab Emirates]]||[[Abu Dhabi]]||AUH||OMAA||[[Abu Dhabi International Airport]]|| ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/direct-flights-to-abu-dhabi-next-destination-of-himalaya-airlines/|title=Direct flights to Abu Dhabi: Next destination of Himalaya Airlines|publisher=Aviation Nepal|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Dubai]]||DWC||OMDW||[[Al Maktoum International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref name=\"AVN\">{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines to shift its base station in Dubai from DWC to DXB Dubai International Airport|url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/himalaya-airlines-shift-base-station-dubai-dwc-dxb-dubai-international-airport/|publisher=Aviation Nepal|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n||DXB||OMDB||[[Dubai International Airport]]||{{terminated}}||<ref name=\"H9W19\"></ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Fleet ==\n[[File:New Livery.jpg|alt=|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 at [[Tribhuvan International Airport]]]]\nHimalaya Airlines operates the following aircraft as of 02 March 2020:<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines fleet information|url=http://himalaya-airlines.com/about/corporate/fleet-information|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines fleet details and history|url=https://m.planespotters.net/airline/Himalaya-Airlines|publisher=PlaneSpotters|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n<center>\n<!-- Please do NOT edit the table unless you know what you are doing -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Himalaya Airlines fleet'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Aircraft\n!rowspan=\"2\"|In Service\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Orders\n!colspan=\"3\"|Passengers\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Note\n|-\n!<abbr title=\"Premium Economy Class\">P</abbr>\n!<abbr title=\"Economy\">Y</abbr>\n!Total\n|-\n|[[Airbus A319-100]]\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|120\n|128\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines inducts brand new A319 into the fleet|url=https://www.spotlightnepal.com/2020/03/03/himalaya-airlines-inducts-brand-new-a319-fleet/|publisher=Spotlight Nepal|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320-200]]\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|150\n|158\n|\n|-\n!Total\n!4\n!&mdash;\n!colspan=\"4\"|\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Services ==\n\n==== Business Class ====\nHimalaya Airlines was the first airline in Nepal to introduce a Premium Economy class. It consists of 8 seats on the Airbus A320 with a four-abreast configuration. The seats are {{convert|26.9|in}} wide with {{convert|43|in}} seat pitch.<ref name=\"Class\">{{cite web |title=Travel Classes |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/travel/travel-classes |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> As of 2020, this section of the aircaft was rebranded as the airlines' [[Business Class]].\n\n==== Economy Class====\nIn Himalaya Airlines' Economy class, the seats are {{convert|17.5|in}} wide with {{convert|30|in}} seat pitch.<ref name=\"Class\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/}}\n{{Commonscat-inline|Himalaya Airlines}}\n\n{{portalbar|Aviation|Nepal}}\n{{Airlines of Nepal}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2014]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Nepal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airline\n| airline = Himalaya Airlines\n| image = Himalaya_Airlines.png\n| image_size = 100\n| alt = Logo of Himalaya Airlines\n| IATA = H9<ref name=\"chavprofile\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ch-aviation.com/portal/airline/HYL | title=Himalaya Airlines | work=[[ch-aviation]] | accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n| ICAO = HIM<ref name=\"chavprofile\" />\n| callsign = HIMALAYA<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.faa.gov/documentLibrary/media/Order/7340_2F_Bsc_w_Chgs_1-3_Contractions.pdf#page=181 | title=7340.2F with Change 1 and Change 2 and Change 3 | work=[[Federal Aviation Administration]] | date=15 September 2016 | accessdate=24 January 2017 | page=3\u20131\u201351}}</ref>\n| founded = 19 August 2014\n| commenced = 31 May 2016\n| aoc = 084/2015<ref>{{cite web |title=Civil aviation Report 2017 |url=http://www.caanepal.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Final-Report-2017.pdf |publisher=Civil Aviation Authority of Nepal |accessdate=14 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907044552/http://www.caanepal.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Final-Report-2017.pdf |archive-date=7 September 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| ceased = \n| bases = \n| hubs = [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] {{small|(Kathmandu)}}\n| secondary_hubs = \n| focus_cities = \n| frequent_flyer = \n| lounge = \n| alliance = \n| fleet_size = 4\n| destinations = 10\n| company_slogan = \n| parent = \n| num_employees = \n| headquarters = [[Gairidhara|Gairidhara, Kathmandu]], Nepal<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us|publisher=Himalaya Airlines|accessdate=7 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118094416/http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us|archive-date=18 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| key_people = {{bulleted list\n|Zhou Enyong<br>{{small|President}}\n|Vijay Shrestha<br>{{small|Vice President}}\n}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Himalaya Airlines''' ({{lang-ne|\u0939\u093f\u092e\u093e\u0932\u092f \u090f\u0905\u0930\u0932\u093e\u0907\u0928\u094d\u0938\u094d}}, ''{{transl|ne|BGN/PCGN|Him\u0101laya earal\u0101ins}}'') is a [[Nepal|Nepalese]] [[airline]] operating from [[Tribhuvan International Airport]] in Kathmandu, Nepal. Himalaya Airlines was founded in 2014 as a [[joint venture]] between Yeti World Investment Group and [[Tibet Airlines]]. It launched operations in May 2016 with a single [[Airbus A320]]. The airline flies to ten destinations as of 24 January 2020.\n\n[[File:D-AVVU -- Himalaya Airlines -- A320-214SL -- MSN 7503 -- 9N-ALV (32049204731).jpg|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 taxiing at [[Hamburg Finkenwerder Airport|Finkenwerder Airport]] in Germany]]\n[[File:9N-ALW@PKX (20191027170009).jpg|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 wearing the new livery on a final approach to Beijing-Daxing.]]\n\n==History==\nHimalaya Airlines is the second attempt of [[Yeti Airlines|Yeti Airlines Group]] to launch an international airline based in Nepal, following the collapse of [[Fly Yeti]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |title=Air Arabia begins Nepal hub operations and launches flyyeti.com |url=http://www.flyyeti.com:80/Air%20Arabia%20begins%20Nepal%20hub%20operations%20and%20launches%20FlyYeti.html |publisher=Fly Yeti |accessdate=1 October 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080206232908/http://www.flyyeti.com/Air%20Arabia%20begins%20Nepal%20hub%20operations%20and%20launches%20FlyYeti.html |archivedate=6 February 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInitially,{{When|date=July 2018}} [[Tibet Airlines]] and the Himalaya Infrastructure Fund had stakes in the airline alongside Yeti World Investment, an affiliate of Yeti Airlines Group.<ref name=\"firstprovingflight\">{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2015-02-27/himalaya-conducts-proving-flight.html | title=Himalaya conducts 'proving' flight | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=27 February 2015 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn order to obtain its [[air operator's certificate]], Himalaya Airlines leased aircraft from Yeti Airlines and conducted its first proving flights in February 2015.<ref name=\"firstprovingflight\" /> Launch plans were delayed by the [[April 2015 Nepal earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-01-27/himalaya-airlines-plans-to-start-ops-by-march-end.html | title=Himalaya Airlines plans to start ops by March-end | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=27 January 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> The airline inducted its first aircraft, an [[Airbus A320]], on March 9 2016.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-03-10/himalaya-airlines-takes-delivery-of-first-aircraft.html | title=Himalaya Airlines takes delivery of first aircraft | work=[[The Kathmandu Post]] | date=10 March 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Himalaya Airlines launched operations on May 31 2016 with flights between [[Kathmandu]] and [[Doha]].<ref name=\"launch31may\">{{cite news | url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2016-07/07/c_135496535.htm | title=China-Nepal JV airline to start daily Kathmandu-Doha flight | work=[[Xinhua News Agency]] | date=7 July 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Flights from Kathmandu to [[Colombo]] started in October, marking the resumption of scheduled flights between Nepal and Sri Lanka after 28 years but the flights were soon suspended.<ref name=\"launchcmb\">{{cite news | url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-begins-kathmandu-colombo-flight/ | title=Himalaya Airlines begins Kathmandu-Colombo flight | work=[[The Himalayan Times]] | date=1 October 2016 | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Himalaya Airlines served as the [[Air transports of heads of state and government#Nepal|governmental aircraft of Nepal]], when Prime Minister [[Khadga Prasad Oli]] used Himalaya's services on his inaugural visit to [[China]]. This was the first time that the head of the Nepalese Government did not use state owned airline; resulting public outcry.<ref>{{cite web|title=PM to fly to China with Himalaya|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-03-18/pm-to-fly-to-china-with-himalaya.html|publisher=The Kathmandu Post|accessdate=1 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airline initially focused on unconventional routes; such as [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]] and [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka]] as opposed to highly demanded middle-eastern destinations but they were quickly terminated. After all, Himalaya ended up operating to [[Dammam]], [[Saudi Arabia]] as well as [[Abu Dhabi]] and [[Dubai]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]]. In the months leading to '''Visit Nepal 2020''', Himalaya focused on the market in China, as Chinese are ranked second among the most number of travellers that visit to Nepal. In October 2019, Himalaya Airlines launched direct service to Beijing's newly constructed [[Beijing Daxing International Airport | Daxing International Airport]] making it the only airline in Nepal to connect the capitals of [[Nepal]] and [[China]].{{cn}}\n\nDuring the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal]], Himalaya Airlines carried out rescue and evacuation charter flights<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines Chartered flight returns back from Guangzhou; Mission Accomplished |url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/himalaya-airlines-chartered-flight-returns-back-from-guangzhou-mission-accomplished/ |publisher=Aviation Nepal |accessdate=29 April 2020}}</ref> while all of its scheduled flights were grounded from March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|title=NAC and Himalaya Airlines suspend flights to Doha|date=2020-03-11|website=The Himalayan Times|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331131329/https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/nac-and-himalaya-airlines-suspend-flights-to-doha/|archive-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n==Corporate affairs==\nAt the time of its establishment, Tibet Airlines held a 49% stake in Himalaya Airlines, while Yeti World Investment (an affiliate of Yeti Airlines Group) owned the remaining 51%.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://nepalitimes.com/article/nation/Nepal-is-still-on-european-safety-blacklist,3442 | title=A Himalayan mess | work=[[Nepali Times]] | date=2016 | accessdate=17 February 2017 | author=Rai, Om}}</ref> Zhao Guo Qiang was the airline's first president while [[Ang Tshering Sherpa (entrepreneur)|Ang Tshering Sherpa]] served as [[chairman of the board]] until his death in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=About us |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170118094416/https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/article/about-us |archivedate=18 January 2017}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, Himalaya Airlines underwent [[restructuring|ownership restructuring]], for which the shares of Tibet Airlines were transferred to [[Tibet Civil Aviation Development and Investment]]. Subsequently, the logo and livery were changed. The blue, dark blue as well as white blend of livery and logo was changed with orange and blue combination. Though, the fuselage retained its white color.<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines announces new partnership with Tibet Civil Aviation |url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2019/09/30/himalaya-airlines-announces-new-partnership-with-tibet-civil-aviation |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=1 October 2019}}</ref> Currently, [[Zhou Enyong]] serves as the president of Himalaya Airlines.<ref>{{cite web |title=Management Team |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/about/corporate/management-team |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe airline is headquartered in [[Gairidhara]], Kathmandu.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/address.php | title=Corporate office address | work=Himalaya Airlines | accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Destinations==\nAs a result of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nepal|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], [[ Nepal Government]] has suspended all domestic and international flights until 15 May 2020.{{cn|date=April 2020}}.\n\nPrior to this, Himalaya Airlines served the following destinations:<ref>{{cite web |title=Flight Schedule|url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/travel/flights-schedule |publisher=Himalayan Airlines |accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Country\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|City\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|IATA\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|ICAO\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Airport\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Notes\n!style=\"background:#008bd1;color: white;\"|Refs\n|-\n|[[Bangladesh]]||[[Dhaka]]||DAC||VGHS||[[Shahjalal International Airport]]||||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-direct-flight-to-dhaka/|title=Himalaya Airlines direct flight to dhaka|publisher=The Himalayan Times|access-date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|[[China]]||[[Beijing]]||PKX||ZBAD||[[Beijing Daxing International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines plans Beijing Daxing launch in late October 2019|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286470/himalaya-airlines-plans-beijing-daxing-launch-in-late-oct-2019/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Changsha]]||CHX||ZGHA||[[Changsha Huanghua International Airport]]||  ||<ref name=\"H9W19\">{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines Winter 2019 network adjustment|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287507/himalaya-airlines-w19-network-adjustment-as-of-08nov19/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Chongqing]]||CKG||ZUCK||[[Chongqing Jiangbei International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya begins direct flights to Chongqing |url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-10-23/himalaya-begins-direct-flights-to-chongqing.html |publisher=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=23 October 2018 |date=23 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines resumes Chongqing service in late-jan 2020|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288631/himalaya-airlines-resumes-chongqing-service-in-late-jan-2020/|publisher=Routes Online|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Guiyang]]||KWE||ZUGY||[[Guiyang Longdongbao International Airport]]||  ||<ref name=\"H9W19\"/>\n|- \n|[[Shenzhen]]||SZX||ZGSZ||[[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport]]||  ||<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prasain |first1=Sangam |title=As other airports institute stringent screening, TIA installs thermal scanners and a health desk |url=https://kathmandupost.com/national/2020/01/28/as-other-airports-institute-stringent-screening-tia-installs-thermal-scanners-and-a-health-desk |website=The Kathmandu Post |publisher=Kantipur Media Group |accessdate=1 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Malaysia]]||[[Kuala Lumpur]]||KUL||WMKK||[[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]]|| ||\n|-\n|[[Myanmar]]||[[Yangon]]||RGN||VYYY||[[Yangon International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref>{{cite web |title=Airline stops Yangon to Kathmandu flights |url=https://www.mmtimes.com/news/airline-stops-yangon-kathmandu-flights.html |publisher=Myanmar Times |accessdate=1 October 2018 |date=18 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Nepal]]||[[Kathmandu]]||KTM||VNKT||[[Tribhuvan International Airport]]||{{Airline hub}}||\n|-\n|[[Qatar]]||[[Doha]]||DOH||OTHH||[[Hamad International Airport]]|| ||\n|-\n|[[Saudi Arabia]]||[[Dammam]]||DMM||OEDF||[[King Fahd International Airport]]|| ||<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines' Festival Bonanza: Daily direct flight from Kathmandu to Dammam|url=http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/press/detail/himalaya-airlines-festival-bonanza-daily-direct-flight-from-kathmandu-to-dammam|publisher=Himalaya Airlines|accessdate=30 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903074206/http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/press/detail/himalaya-airlines-festival-bonanza-daily-direct-flight-from-kathmandu-to-dammam|archive-date=3 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Sri Lanka]]||[[Colombo]]||CMB||VCBI||[[Bandaranaike International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref>{{cite web |title=Himalaya Airlines launches inaugural flight to Colombo |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/business/himalaya-airlines-launches-inaugural-flight-colombo/ |publisher=The Himalayan Times |accessdate=1 October 2018 |date=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[United Arab Emirates]]||[[Abu Dhabi]]||AUH||OMAA||[[Abu Dhabi International Airport]]|| ||<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/direct-flights-to-abu-dhabi-next-destination-of-himalaya-airlines/|title=Direct flights to Abu Dhabi: Next destination of Himalaya Airlines|publisher=Aviation Nepal|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Dubai]]||DWC||OMDW||[[Al Maktoum International Airport]]||{{Terminated}}||<ref name=\"AVN\">{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines to shift its base station in Dubai from DWC to DXB Dubai International Airport|url=https://www.aviationnepal.com/himalaya-airlines-shift-base-station-dubai-dwc-dxb-dubai-international-airport/|publisher=Aviation Nepal|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n||DXB||OMDB||[[Dubai International Airport]]||{{terminated}}||<ref name=\"H9W19\"></ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== Fleet ==\n[[File:New Livery.jpg|alt=|thumb|A Himalaya Airlines Airbus A320 at [[Tribhuvan International Airport]]]]\nHimalaya Airlines operates the following aircraft as of 02 March 2020:<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines fleet information|url=http://himalaya-airlines.com/about/corporate/fleet-information|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines fleet details and history|url=https://m.planespotters.net/airline/Himalaya-Airlines|publisher=PlaneSpotters|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n<center>\n<!-- Please do NOT edit the table unless you know what you are doing -->\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse;text-align:center\"\n|+ '''Himalaya Airlines fleet'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Aircraft\n!rowspan=\"2\"|In Service\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Orders\n!colspan=\"3\"|Passengers\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Note\n|-\n!<abbr title=\"Premium Economy Class\">P</abbr>\n!<abbr title=\"Economy\">Y</abbr>\n!Total\n|-\n|[[Airbus A319-100]]\n|1\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|120\n|128\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Himalaya Airlines inducts brand new A319 into the fleet|url=https://www.spotlightnepal.com/2020/03/03/himalaya-airlines-inducts-brand-new-a319-fleet/|publisher=Spotlight Nepal|access-date=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Airbus A320-200]]\n|3\n|&mdash;\n|8\n|150\n|158\n|\n|-\n!Total\n!4\n!&mdash;\n!colspan=\"4\"|\n|}\n</center>\n\n== Services ==\n\n==== Premium Economy Class ====\nHimalaya Airlines was the first airline in Nepal to introduce a Premium Economy class. It consists of 8 seats on the Airbus A320 with a four-abreast configuration. The seats are {{convert|26.9|in}} wide with {{convert|43|in}} seat pitch.<ref name=\"Class\">{{cite web |title=Travel Classes |url=https://www.himalaya-airlines.com/travel/travel-classes |publisher=Himalaya Airlines |accessdate=24 April 2019}}</ref> As of 2020, this section of the aircaft was rebranded as the airlines' [[Business Class]].\n==== Economy Class====\nIn Himalaya Airlines' Economy class, the seats are {{convert|17.5|in}} wide with {{convert|30|in}} seat pitch.<ref name=\"Class\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.himalaya-airlines.com/}}\n{{Commonscat-inline|Himalaya Airlines}}\n\n{{portalbar|Aviation|Nepal}}\n{{Airlines of Nepal}}\n\n[[Category:Airlines of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2014]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in Nepal]]\n", "name_user": "GERNPL", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Himalaya_Airlines"}
{"title_page": "Thousand Buddha Mountain", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2007}}\n[[Image:Qianfoshan ridge.jpg|thumb|239x239px|View along the ridge of the hill from the western side|alt=]]\nThe '''Thousand Buddha Mountain''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u5343|\u4f5b|\u5c71}}|p={{linktext|Qi\u0101n| F\u00f3| Sh\u0101n}}}}) is a hill located about 2.5 kilometers southeast of the city of [[Jinan]], the capital of [[Shandong]] [[Province of China|Province]], [[China]]. It covers 1.518 square kilometers (375.1 acres) and has a peak of 285 meters (935 ft) above sea level. It is renowned for its numerous [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] images which have been carved out of the hill's rock faces or free-standing structures erect since the times of the [[Sui Dynasty]] (581-618) and its Xingguochan Temple. It is considered as one of the \"Three Greatest Attractions in Jinan\" together with [[Baotu Spring]] and [[Daming Lake]]. It is also one of the 4A-rated [[Tourist attractions in China]]. Thousand Buddha Mountain is opened up as a public park in 1959, rated as AAAA-rated Tourist Attractions of China in 2005, and rated as National Park of China in March 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jnqianfoshan.com/index.html|title=Jinan Qianfo Mountain Scenic Official SIte|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legend==\nAccording to local tradition, the legendary [[Emperor Shun]] was credited to open up land and cultivate under the mountain. Thus, the Thousand Buddha Mountain is also known as the Shungeng Hill (meaning the hill where Shun cultivated).<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nAccording to a legend related in the ''Youyang Zazu'' (''Youyang Miscellanies'') by the [[Tang Dynasty]] writer [[Duan Chengshi]] (800-863), the Thousand Buddha Mountain was originally located by the sea and the sea god had locked it in place there by a large lock in order to prevent the god in charge of the mountains from moving it around. However, eventually the lock broke and the mountain was hurled through the air into its present position. An artwork shaped as a large lock and a piece of chain has been placed on the summit of the mountain as a reference to the legend.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Qianfoshan buddha statues1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Buddha statues in a cliff south of the Xingguochan Temple]]\nBuddhism became popular in the Jinan area during the reign of [[Emperor Wen of Sui|Emperor Wen]], the founder of the [[Sui Dynasty]]. With Buddhism, monks came to area and chiseled Buddha statues out of the flanks of the hill, which was originally called ''Miji Hill'' or ''Li Hill''. A temple, called the ''Thousand Buddha Temple'' (Qianfosi), was founded at the foot of the hill. Eventually, the hill was renamed after the temple into \"Thousand Buddha Mountain\". One of the old names, ''Li Hill'' (Li Shan), survives in the name of ''Lishan Road'', the major avenue which runs through Jinan towards the Thousand Buddha Mountain in north-south direction.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Main Attractions ==\n\n=== Thousand Buddha Cliff ===\nThe [[Thousand-Buddha Cliff]] is located on the northern flank of the hill behind the Xingguochan Temple (s. below). The foot of the cliff is pierced by five caves, which are named (from west to east): Longquan (meaning Dragon Spring) Cave, Jile (meaning Extremely Happy) Cave, Qianlou (probably a person's name) Cave, and Luzhu (probably a person's name) Cave.  The caves' height ranges from 3&nbsp;meters down to only 20&nbsp;centimeters. About 130 Buddha statues which were carved into Thousand-Buddha Cliff during the Sui period remain today. The Jile Cave houses 16 Buddha statues, the tallest of which is 3&nbsp;meters high.\n\n=== Xingguochan Temple ===\n[[Image:Qianfoshan buddha statues2.jpg|right|thumb|218x218px|Buddha statues in a cave south of the Xingguochan Temple]]\nAlong with the Buddha statues, temples and other buildings were erected on the hill. The most renowned of these structures is the ''Xingguochan Temple'' ({{zh|c=\u5174\u56fd\u7985\u5bfa|p=Xing Guo Chan Si}}, literally: \"Development of the Country Buddhist Temple\") which was originally built during the reign of [[Emperor Taizong of Tang|Emperor Taizhong]] of [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] as an expansion of the Sui-Dynasty Qianfo Temple. Further enlargements were undertaken during the [[Song Dynasty]], but the temple was destroyed by war afterwards. Rebuilding was undertaken in 1468, during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. The Guanying Hall, the Foye Hall, and the Thousand-Hands Buddha statue were added during the [[Qing Dynasty]].\nThe temple is located about halfway up the hill and can be reached via 300 stone steps. A large inscription (total area about 15&nbsp;square meters) cut into the cliff face to the southwest of the identifies it as the \"Number One Temple\" (Di Yi Mi Hua). The temple's courtyards feature several stone tablets bearing inscriptions from renowned calligraphers. In one of the temple's courtyards stands a sculpture of the legendary [[Emperor Shun]], who is\u2014according to the local tradition\u2014credited with first ploughing the soil in Jinan as well as with inventing the writing brush. Because of its mythological association with Emperor Shun, the Thousand Buddha hill is also known as ''Shungeng Hill''. The main structure of the temple are: Grand Prayer Hall, [[Guanying]] Hall, [[Dharma]] Hall, [[Maitreya]] Hall, and the Buddhist Scripture building. Lishanyuan courtyard, to the east of the temple, is surrounded by sites of worship belonging to [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]], and Buddhism. The names of these buildings are: the Shun and the Luban Ancestral Temples, the Wenchang (\"Develop the Culture\") Cabinet, and the Yilan Kiosk. The temple has been the site of two annual temple fairs held on the 3rd day of the third month and 9th day of the 9th month of the Chinese [[Lunar Calendar]] since the times of the [[Yuan Dynasty]]. It was burned down in wars and rebuild during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. Other notable buildings on the hill are: the ''Pagoda Tree Pavilion'' (Tang Dynasty), ''Cloud Passing Zen Temple'', and the ''Tanghuai Kiosk''.[[Image:qianfoshan xingguochantemple.jpg|left|thumb|236x236px|East gate of Xingguochan Temple]]Many of the statues on the Thousand Buddha Mountain were damaged or lost during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but restoration started in 1979 already. Since then, many new statues have been added. The largest new statues are a 20&nbsp;meter-tall sitting Maitreya Buddha completed in 2000 and lying Buddha with a [[swastika]] on his chest. The latter statue was carved out of [[granite]] in 1996, has a length of 10&nbsp;meters and weighs approximately 50 [[tonnes]].\n\n=== Myriad Buddha Cave ===\n[[File:QianFoShan.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:QianFoShan.jpg|thumb|244x244px|Maitreya Statue]]\nThe Thousand Buddha Mountain Public Park has been developed extensively for\u2014mostly local tourism\u2014by the creation of access roads and walking paths as well the addition of [[amusement park]] features such as a 600&nbsp;meter-long [[chairlift]], a summer slide (the \"Qineng Slide\") down the hill, a [[kart racing]] track, and numerous souvenir stalls (one of which was placed right at the summit as of 2006). A major tourist attraction is the ''Myriad Buddha Cave'' (Wanfo Dong) at the foot of the hill's northern slope. Inside the more than 500&nbsp;meter-long artificial cave, late-20th-century recreations of Buddhist statues from four famous Chinese grottoes ([[Dunhuang]] and [[Maiji Shan]] in [[Gansu]] Province, [[Longmen Grottoes|Longmen]] in [[Henan]] Province, [[Yun Gang]] in [[Shanxi]] Province) are on display. The original artworks were created during the [[Northern Wei Dynasty|Northern Wei]], [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]], and [[Song Dynasty|Song]] dynasties. According to the operators (information provided on the backside of the entrance ticket as of 2006), around 28 000 Buddhist images are on display inside the cave, the biggest statue\u2014a lying Buddha\u2014is 28&nbsp;meters long.\n\n=== Maitreya Garden ===\nLocated in the east part of the mountain, the Maitreya Garden was built in 2000 with Japanese Corporate Myokoen as a China-Japan Friendship Garden. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com.cn/GB/channel4/981/20000921/243522.html|title=The China-Japan Friendship Garden Constructed in Jinan|last=|first=|date=Sep 21, 2000|website=People|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref> The garden covers 30 thousand square meters, including the [[Maitreya]] statue, Sakura garden, and some other affiliated structures, which is a blend of Chinese and Japanese styles of garden architecture. The whole statue has a height of 30 meters, thus it is known as \"the number one largest Buddha north of Yangze River.\" The information about Maitreya is carved behind the statue on an annular rock face. The carvings are 36 meters long and 3.5 meters high, covering 126 square meters.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Annual Events ==\n[[File:Qianfoshan New Year Temple Fair.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Qianfoshan%20New%20Year%20Temple%20Fair.jpg|left|thumb|192x192px|Qianfoshan Spring Festival Temple Fair]]\n\n=== Lunar New Year Praying Temple Fair ===\nAs one of the most important festivals of the year, [[Lunar New Year]] is the time for Chinese people to pray for good luck for the upcoming year. Every year during Spring Festival, thousands of people visit the Xingguochan Temple to burn incense and pray for their loved ones and for a peaceful year. There is also the temple fair for tourists to feel in flavor of the Spring Festival with folk performances and artifacts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1624722191907430955&wfr=spider&for=pc|title=Jinan: Spring Festival Temple Fair at Qianfoshan|last=|first=|date=Feb 6, 2019|website=Shaanxi Fazhiwang|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:QianfoshanMiaohui.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:QianfoshanMiaohui.jpg|thumb|215x215px|Tanghulu Booth at Qianfoshan Miaohui]]\n\n=== Qixi Festival Blind Dates ===\nDuring the week of [[Qixi Festival]], the Chinese Valentine's Day, the park holds blind dates for single men and women from Jinan and other places. Mainly in their twenties or thirties, participants post their information onto the board while searching for ones they have interests in. Parents who wish their children to get married also go up the hill to find a date for their children. By 2019, the event had been held for 13 times. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sd.dzwww.com/sdnews/201908/t20190808_19035441.htm|title=Romance on the Rainy Day of Qixi Festival!|last=|first=|date=Aug 8, 2019|website=Dazhongwang|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Double Ninth Festival Temple Fair ===\nThe [[Double Ninth Festival]] is a traditional Chinese festival on the ninth day of the ninth month in [[Lunar calendar|Lunar Calendar]]. While it is customary to climbing a high mountain, Thousand Buddha Mountain Scenic Spot holds annual temple fair around that time of the year. Exhibition includes artistic performance, folk handicrafts and local souvenirs, agricultural products, and traditional food and snacks. On the date of the festival in 2019, the total number of tourists reached over 62,000. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1646778941391219960&wfr=spider&for=pc|title=Jinan \"Teachers\" Love Qianfoshan Miaohui: Over 62,000 Tourists on the Day of Double Ninth Festival|last=|first=|date=Oct 8, 2019|website=Qilu Wanbao|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\n[[Image:qianfoshan northside.jpg|thumb|right|284x284px|Northern slope of the hill]]\nThe Thousand Buddha Mountain Public Park is flanked by a cemetery honoring the fallen of the [[Xinhai Revolution]] of 1911 on the east side, the former site of Shandong Provincial Museum to the northeast, and the Jinan Botanical Garden on the west side.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thousand-Buddha Cliff]]\n*[[Buddhism in China]]\n*[[List of sites in Jinan]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.china-sd.net/eng/sdtravel/scenery/20.asp article on \"Shandong On Internet\"]\n\n[[Category:History of Shandong]]\n[[Category:Buddhist temples in Shandong]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Shandong]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jinan]]\n[[Category:Hills of China]]\n[[Category:AAAA-rated tourist attractions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2007}}\n[[Image:Qianfoshan ridge.jpg|thumb|239x239px|View along the ridge of the hill from the western side|alt=]]\nThe '''Thousand Buddha Mountain''' ({{zh|c={{linktext|\u5343|\u4f5b|\u5c71}}|p={{linktext|Qi\u0101n| F\u00f3| Sh\u0101n}}}}) is a hill located about 2.5 kilometers southeast of the city of [[Jinan]], the capital of [[Shandong]] [[Province of China|Province]], [[China]]. It covers 1.518 square kilometers (375.1 acres) and has a peak of 285 meters (935 ft) above sea level. It is renowned for its numerous [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] images which have been carved out of the hill's rock faces or free-standing structures erect since the times of the [[Sui Dynasty]] (581-618) and its Xingguochan Temple. It is considered as one of the \"Three Greatest Attractions in Jinan\" together with [[Baotu Spring]] and [[Daming Lake]]. It is also one of the 4A-rated [[Tourist attractions in China]]. Thousand Buddha Mountain is opened up as a public park in 1959, rated as AAAA-rated Tourist Attractions of China in 2005, and rated as National Park of China in March 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.jnqianfoshan.com/index.html|title=Jinan Qianfo Mountain Scenic Official SIte|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legend==\nAccording to local tradition, the legendary [[Emperor Shun]] was credited to open up land and cultivate under the mountain. Thus, the Thousand Buddha Mountain is also known as the Shungeng Hill (meaning the hill where Shun cultivated). \n\nAccording to a legend related in the ''Youyang Zazu'' (''Youyang Miscellanies'') by the [[Tang Dynasty]] writer [[Duan Chengshi]] (800-863), the Thousand Buddha Mountain was originally located by the sea and the sea god had locked it in place there by a large lock in order to prevent the god in charge of the mountains from moving it around. However, eventually the lock broke and the mountain was hurled through the air into its present position. An artwork shaped as a large lock and a piece of chain has been placed on the summit of the mountain as a reference to the legend.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Qianfoshan buddha statues1.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Buddha statues in a cliff south of the Xingguochan Temple]]\nBuddhism became popular in the Jinan area during the reign of\n[[Emperor Wen of Sui|Emperor Wen]], the founder of the [[Sui Dynasty]]. With Buddhism, monks came to area and chiseled Buddha statues out of the flanks of the hill, which was originally called ''Miji Hill'' or ''Li Hill''. A temple, called the ''Thousand Buddha Temple'' (Qianfosi) was founded at the foot of the hill. Eventually, the hill was renamed after the temple into \"Thousand Buddha Mountain\". One of the old names, ''Li Hill'' (Li Shan), survives in the name of ''Lishan Road'', the major avenue which runs through Jinan towards the Thousand Buddha Mountain in north-south direction.\n\n== Main Attractions ==\n\n=== Thousand Buddha Cliff ===\nThe [[Thousand-Buddha Cliff]] is located on the northern flank of the hill behind the Xingguochan Temple (s. below). The foot of the cliff is pierced by five caves, which are named (from west to east): Longquan (Dragon Spring) Cave, Jile (Extremely Happy) Cave, Qianlou (probably a person's name) Cave, and Luzhu (probably a person's name) Cave.  The caves' height ranges from 3&nbsp;meters down to only 20&nbsp;centimeters. About 130 Buddha statues which were carved into Thousand-Buddha Cliff during the Sui period remain today. The Jile Cave houses 16 Buddha statues, the tallest of which is 3&nbsp;m high.\n\n=== Xingguochan Temple ===\n[[Image:Qianfoshan buddha statues2.jpg|right|thumb|218x218px|Buddha statues in a cave south of the Xingguochan Temple]]\nAlong with the Buddha statues, temples and other buildings were erected on the hill. The most renowned of these structures is the ''Xingguochan Temple'' ({{zh|c=\u5174\u56fd\u7985\u5bfa|p=Xing Guo Chan Si}}, literally: \"Development of the Country Buddhist Temple\") which was originally built during the reign of [[Emperor Taizong of Tang|Emperor Taizhong]] of [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] as an expansion of the Sui-Dynasty Qianfo Temple. Further enlargements were undertaken during the [[Song Dynasty]], but the temple was destroyed by war afterwards. Rebuilding was undertaken in 1468, during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. The Guanying Hall, the Foye Hall, and the Thousand-Hands Buddha statue were added during the [[Qing Dynasty]].\nThe temple is located about halfway up the hill and can be reached via 300 stone steps. A large inscription (total area about 15&nbsp;square meters) cut into the cliff face to the southwest of the identifies it as the \"Number One Temple\" (Di Yi Mi Hua). The temple's courtyards feature several stone tablets bearing inscriptions from renowned calligraphers. In one of the temple's courtyards stands a sculpture of the legendary [[Emperor Shun]], who is\u2014according to the local tradition\u2014credited with first ploughing the soil in Jinan as well as with inventing the writing brush. Because of its mythological association with Emperor Shun, the Thousand Buddha hill is also known as ''Shungeng Hill''. The main structure of the temple are: Grand Prayer Hall, [[Guanying]] Hall, [[Dharma]] Hall, [[Maitreya]] Hall, and the Buddhist Scripture building. Lishanyuan courtyard, to the east of the temple, is surrounded by sites of worship belonging to [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]], and Buddhism. The names of these buildings are: the Shun and the Luban Ancestral Temples, the Wenchang (\"Develop the Culture\") Cabinet, and the Yilan Kiosk. The temple has been the site of two annual temple fairs held on the 3rd day of the third month and 9th day of the 9th month of the Chinese [[Lunar Calendar]] since the times of the [[Yuan Dynasty]]. It was burned down in wars and rebuild during the [[Ming Dynasty]]. Other notable buildings on the hill are: the ''Pagoda Tree Pavilion'' (Tang Dynasty), ''Cloud Passing Zen Temple'', and the ''Tanghuai Kiosk''.[[Image:qianfoshan xingguochantemple.jpg|left|thumb|236x236px|East gate of Xingguochan Temple]]Many of the statues on the Thousand Buddha Mountain were damaged or lost during the [[Cultural Revolution]], but restoration started in 1979 already. Since then, many new statues have been added. The largest new statues are a 20&nbsp;meter-tall sitting Maitreya Buddha completed in 2000 and lying Buddha with a [[swastika]] on his chest. The latter statue was carved out of [[granite]] in 1996, has a length of 10&nbsp;meters and weighs approximately 50 [[tonnes]].\n\n=== Myriad Buddha Cave ===\n[[File:QianFoShan.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:QianFoShan.jpg|thumb|244x244px|Maitreya Statue]]\nThe Thousand Buddha Mountain Public Park has been developed extensively for\u2014mostly local tourism\u2014by the creation of access roads and walking paths as well the addition of [[amusement park]] features such as a 600&nbsp;meter-long [[chairlift]], a summer slide (the \"Qineng Slide\") down the hill, a [[kart racing]] track, and numerous souvenir stalls (one of which was placed right at the summit as of 2006). A major tourist attraction is the ''Myriad Buddha Cave'' (Wanfo Dong) at the foot of the hill's northern slope. Inside the more than 500&nbsp;meter-long artificial cave, late-20th-century recreations of Buddhist statues from four famous Chinese grottoes ([[Dunhuang]] and [[Maiji Shan]] in [[Gansu]] Province, [[Longmen Grottoes|Longmen]] in [[Henan]] Province, [[Yun Gang]] in [[Shanxi]] Province) are on display. The original artworks were created during the [[Northern Wei Dynasty|Northern Wei]], [[Tang Dynasty|Tang]], and [[Song Dynasty|Song]] dynasties. According to the operators (information provided on the backside of the entrance ticket as of 2006), around 28 000 Buddhist images are on display inside the cave, the biggest statue\u2014a lying Buddha\u2014is 28&nbsp;meters long.\n\n=== Maitreya Garden ===\nLocated in the east part of the mountain, the Maitreya Garden was built in 2000 with Japanese Corporate Myokoen as a China-Japan Friendship Garden. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com.cn/GB/channel4/981/20000921/243522.html|title=The China-Japan Friendship Garden Constructed in Jinan|last=|first=|date=Sep 21, 2000|website=People|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref> The garden covers 30 thousand square meters, including the [[Maitreya]] statue, Sakura garden, and some other affiliated structures, which is a blend of Chinese and Japanese styles of garden architecture. The whole statue has a height of 30 meters, thus it is known as \"the number one largest Buddha north of Yangze River.\" The information about Maitreya is carved behind the statue on an annular rock face. The carvings are 36 meters long and 3.5 meters high, covering 126 square meters.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Annual Events ==\n[[File:Qianfoshan New Year Temple Fair.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Qianfoshan%20New%20Year%20Temple%20Fair.jpg|left|thumb|192x192px|Qianfoshan Spring Festival Temple Fair]]\n\n=== Lunar New Year Praying Temple Fair ===\nAs one of the most important festivals of the year, [[Lunar New Year]] is the time for Chinese people to pray for good luck for the upcoming year. Every year during Spring Festival, thousands of people visit the Xingguochan Temple to burn incense and pray for their loved ones and for a peaceful year. There is also the temple fair for tourists to feel in flavor of the Spring Festival with folk performances and artifacts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1624722191907430955&wfr=spider&for=pc|title=Jinan: Spring Festival Temple Fair at Qianfoshan|last=|first=|date=Feb 6, 2019|website=Shaanxi Fazhiwang|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n[[File:QianfoshanMiaohui.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:QianfoshanMiaohui.jpg|thumb|215x215px|Tanghulu Booth at Qianfoshan Miaohui]]\n\n=== Qixi Festival Blind Dates ===\nDuring the week of [[Qixi Festival]], the Chinese Valentine's Day, the park holds blind dates for single men and women from Jinan and other places. Mainly in their twenties or thirties, participants post their information onto the board while searching for ones they have interests in. Parents who wish their children to get married also go up the hill to find a date for their children. By 2019, the event had been held for 13 times. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sd.dzwww.com/sdnews/201908/t20190808_19035441.htm|title=Romance on the Rainy Day of Qixi Festival!|last=|first=|date=Aug 8, 2019|website=Dazhongwang|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Double Ninth Festival Temple Fair ===\nThe [[Double Ninth Festival]] is a traditional Chinese festival on the ninth day of the ninth month in [[Lunar calendar|Lunar Calendar]]. While it is customary to climbing a high mountain, Thousand Buddha Mountain Scenic Spot holds annual temple fair around that time of the year. Exhibition includes artistic performance, folk handicrafts and local souvenirs, agricultural products, and traditional food and snacks. On the date of the festival in 2019, the total number of tourists reached over 62,000. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baijiahao.baidu.com/s?id=1646778941391219960&wfr=spider&for=pc|title=Jinan \"Teachers\" Love Qianfoshan Miaohui: Over 62,000 Tourists on the Day of Double Ninth Festival|last=|first=|date=Oct 8, 2019|website=Qilu Wanbao|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Apr 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Location==\n[[Image:qianfoshan northside.jpg|thumb|right|284x284px|Northern slope of the hill]]\nThe Thousand Buddha Mountain Public Park is flanked by a cemetery honoring the fallen of the [[Xinhai Revolution]] of 1911 on the east side, the former site of Shandong Provincial Museum to the northeast, and the Jinan Botanical Garden on the west side.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Thousand-Buddha Cliff]]\n*[[Buddhism in China]]\n*[[List of sites in Jinan]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.china-sd.net/eng/sdtravel/scenery/20.asp article on \"Shandong On Internet\"]\n\n[[Category:History of Shandong]]\n[[Category:Buddhist temples in Shandong]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Shandong]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Jinan]]\n[[Category:Hills of China]]\n[[Category:AAAA-rated tourist attractions]]\n", "name_user": "HelenaSun", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added several citations", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thousand_Buddha_Mountain"}
